content:
General Nutrition Centers relies heavily on the Invent Store-to-Store transfer tool. They use it for the following use cases:

- Weekly rebalancing of inventory among stores
- Transferring all inventory out of closing stores
- Assortment localization
- Filling new store shelves from other stores
- Transferring out partial units for selected items in a store

## About Store-to-Store Transfer

The Store-to-Store Transfer service is a general purpose tool for moving inventory between brick and mortar stores. Depending on the particular use case, it tries to move units of inventory to or from the stores that will result in the highest system-wide utilization. It supports the following general types of transfers:

metadata.title: Intro to Store-to-Store Transfer at GNC

content:
result in the highest system-wide utilization. It supports the following general types of transfers:

- Performance: rebalance inventory across sets of stores based on current selling and inventory conditions
- Stock Clearance: Remove inventory from a store and distribute it to other stores
- Stock Consolidation: Move inventory to a store from a set of other stores, prioritizing the units that are least likely to sell in their current location
- Capacity Transfer: Move inventory out of a store when it exceeds the space available for the given item

At GNC, we currently use Performance transfers on an automated weekly basis, and Stock Clearance and Consolidation on an ad hoc basis for the use cases described above. GNC does not currently use Capacity transfers.

## Using STST with GNC

metadata.title: Intro to Store-to-Store Transfer at GNC

content:
he use cases described above. GNC does not currently use Capacity transfers.

## Using STST with GNC

The STST tool has a legacy user interface (which is the one currently used for GNC), and a new Cheetah-based interface (not yet available for GNC). Although both versions enable product and store selection, they don’t provide enough features to support “end-to-end” setup of the typical clearance or consolidation transfer for GNC. That is to say, you must run SQL Queries against the GNC database to gather lists of products and stores, which you can then load into the UI, rather than using filters built into the UI to do the work for you. For that reason, we have created a set of SQL queries, along with a recipe for using them in conjunction with the STST tool.

## GNC Use Case Summary

The table below summarizes the essential elements of processes used to execute the GNC use cases. Click on the link in the Use Case column to see the detailed steps to perform.

| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Weekly Rebalancing | Performance | Weekly | Automated process initiated on Sundays | This is a fully automated process |
| Store Closing | Stock Clearance | Ad hoc | Move all units of eligible products out of a store - most often used when a store is closing | Get a list of products at the closing store that are eligible for transferGet a list of stores that are eligible to receive the unitsInitiate a Stock Clearance run |
| Assortment Localization | Stock Clearance | Ad hoc | Move out all units of products that are not part of the new store assortment | Get a list of products at the store that are not part of the new assortmentGet a list of stores that are eligible to receive the unitsInitiate a Stock Clearance run |

| New Store Fill-In | Stock Consolidation | Ad hoc | Move units into a new store for items that are in short supply from the vendor | Get a list of products that are needed in the new store, along with the desired number of unitsGet a list of stores that are eligible to deliver the unitsInitiate a Stock Consolidation run |

unitsGet a list of stores that are eligible to deliver the unitsInitiate a Stock Consolidation run |
| Excess Inventory Reduction | Stock Clearance | Ad hoc | Move excess units of one or more products out of a store. Note that this use case is rarely used; the weekly rebalancing run should normally take care of this, but occasionally there is a request to remove more units than rebalancing would achieve. | Get a list of products and the desired number of units to be removedGet a list of stores that are eligible to receive the unitsRun a query to set up minimum stock thresholds for the origin storeInitiate a Stock Clearance run for the set of products, making sure to uncheck the custom parameter “Ignore Minimum Stocks in Stock Clearance” |

## Validating The Results of a Run

metadata.title: Intro to Store-to-Store Transfer at GNC

content:
he custom parameter “Ignore Minimum Stocks in Stock Clearance” |

## Validating The Results of a Run

STST produces a file that has a row for each origin-destination-product triplet, specifying the number of units to transfer, as well as some other supporting details. Validation of this file is strongly recommended - even someone experienced with the process can easily make a mistake in the setup process, so checking a few key features of the results will save time and effort.

Currently, there is no summarizing report that allows for quick validation of the results of a run. Consequently, we have put together some excel workbook templates that can be used to summarize the file contents and allow you to confidently deliver the results to GNC. These templates are described in the detailed steps for each of the use cases.

metadata.title: Intro to Store-to-Store Transfer at GNC

When GNC closes a store, they first turn off replenishment. They then wait 8 weeks for inventory to sell down naturally. Then they request a Store Clearance transfer run to move remaining inventory to other locations.

There are several rules that restrict the transfer of products from one location to another:

- Food and drink items cannot be transferred to other stores (has to do with fragility and packaging issues)
- Some states have conditions that make transfers into or out of the state problematic. For this reason, transfers for stores closing in those states can only be to other stores within the state. Those states are:CaliforniaHawaiiAlaskaPuerto Rico

When GNC opens a new store, they often find that they can’t provide every item it needs through normal replenishment because of vendor fulfillment issues. For items that cannot be obtained from the warehouse after repeated tries, they then use STST to get the desired units from other locations that have more than needed.

The basic process is as follows:

1. Get a list of products and quantities needed for the new store - create a file that has product, store, quantity, as defined for a Consolidation run. There will only be one store, which is the new store.
2. Create a new scenario based on the default, that has a region defined that includes the new store. Mark the new store as blocked for transfer out.
3. Run the consolidation run, and specify to optimize by Region. This will limit the contributing stores to the ones in the same region as the new store.
